  "tables": [
    {
      "block_id": "23c4750c-f3ba-805c-bb4e-c5dca0a43b67",
      "heading": "Summary Table REC",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Recommender System Type",
          "Target of Recommendation",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Initialization Method",
          "Updates to Recommendations",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Recommendation types",
          "Evaluation",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "MOOC",
          "E-Learning",
          "Content-based filtering",
          "Courses to Take ",
          "168664 XueTxang users",
          "6410 courses",
          "Course Descriptors\nEnrollment history\n",
          "Entity Embeddings are learned using TransH.\n\nCourse Information is done via the creation of separate embeddings for pre-requisite courses, curreent courses and parallel courses.\n\nFor users, Knowledge Extraction, it takes the sequence of the courses taken and computes the average representation aacross the different dimensions.\n",
          "- Retraining after a learner takes a course.",
          "Dimensions of Word Embedings are set to 100.\n\nSeparate layers are creation:\n- Creation of a Curse Knowledge Graph to understand course relationships\n\n- Knowledge Background from users: Uses sequences of courses taken\n\nFinal prediction is obtained via the product bbetween user embedding and the course embeddings",
          "Top-K Courses to take ",
          "{AUC: 0.9143 - HRL, HR@5: 0.8269 - Proposed Model, HR@10: 0.8785 - Proposed Model, NDCG@5: 0.6808 - Proposed Model, NDCG@10: 0.6973 - Proposed Model, MRR: 0.6433 - Proposed Model}",
          "Authors propose a new N architecture that inclues different modules:\n\nKnowledge extraction Module:  includes the representations of all courses available in the platform\n\nUser Knowledge Background: Creates a representation of the user’s knowledge based on the courses taken up to this point → uses as input the sequences of courses taken.\n\nUser Interest: Results from the product of the user’s history with the representation of each candidate course → leads to a prediction of probability of enrollment.\n\nModel outperforms other baseliines considered for a similar task.\n\n",
          "- Does not consider user history beyond the sequence of courses taken."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 6
    }
  ],
